英文虎报 | 2014-10-30 \par
P22| Supplement| By Joanne Lee \par 

High prices here to stay \par
\par
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ \par









\par\par  Despite the ongoing \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0   protests, expensive secondary market  prices and strong take-up of primary  homes at launches indicate fundamental  demand continues to support the market. \par\par Overall, prices for mass residential  properties have risen 8 percent so far this  year, while those in the luxury sector  have fallen 1.2 percent. \par\par The prolonged \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0   protests and increasing competition  among new projects will prompt buyers  to become more cautious, and the sales  response may not be as robust compared  with previous months.  \par\par The key factor driving up prices is  the imbalance between supply and demand. \par\par Underestimates of demand, coupled  with a lack of supply in the current market - particularly a dearth of small to  medium-sized flats in urban areas - explain why prices remain high despite  measures to cool demand. The market's  downward cycle is yet to be seen. \par\par Once pent-up demand is absorbed,  new supply will rise, and a rate hike will  be closer. But higher rates are unlikely  to create a major disturbance in the  property market. \par\par Today, high construction costs and  strong demand are combining to keep  prices high, although new private housing supply will continue growing over  the next three to four years. \par\par While land in urban areas remains  expensive, prices in the New Territories  are softening as developers factor in  high-risk margins for bids that take into  consideration sustained land supply in  the area, future absorption and higher  construction costs. \par\par Wages are a big part of construction  costs.  \par\par Over the past few years, the situation  has become problematic, as several key  infrastructure projects have soaked up  workers, creating a labor shortage and  pushing wages higher.  \par\par Housing supply is only one of the  factors affecting price movements.  With construction costs continuing to  rise and urban land still expensive,  developers will be reluctant to slash  asking prices. \par\par Prices will see only a slight improvement unless interest rates increase  sharply, or we experience another economic crisis. \par\par Joanne Lee is manager of research  and advisory at Colliers International.  Contact her at joanne.lee@colliers.com  \par
