Luxury flats demand returns in fine style \par
\par
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ \par









\par\par  Sales of luxury flats have regained momentum after sagging for more than a  year, as developers marked down prices  and the government eased market  cooling measures unleashing pent-up demand from local and mainland buyers  alike. \par\par "Prices of luxury homes have  retreated to a reasonable level in a market  denominated by small and medium  flats,'' said Jeffrey Ng Chong-yip, senior  executive director at Hong Kong Property Services. "And that has revived demand from upgraders.'' \par\par In the third quarter, 559 registrations  of private home transactions valued  above HK$20 million were recorded -  more than double the 218 in the previous  three months, according to Land Registry data. In the same period last year,  there were just 52.  \par\par Analysts expect prices of upscale  properties to climb by up to 5 percent  in the fourth quarter. \par\par When Swire Properties (1972)  launched its Mid-Levels West development Arezzo last month, it reaped  HK$1.23 billion as the first batch of 50  apartments was quickly bought. \par\par Even the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0  protests  failed to deter big-ticket deals. So far  this month, New World Development  (0017) has raked in as much as HK$5.5  billion, after launching 250 homes in  three batches at its Pavilia Hill project  in Tin Hau, selling 220 flats or 88  percent of the total. \par\par The first batch of Arezzo was priced  at an average of HK$27,159 per sellable  square foot, about 17 percent below the  HK$32,837 of Argenta, another Swire  project in Mid-Levels West that was  unveiled a year earlier. \par\par The Pavilia Hill made its debut at  an average price of about 10 percent  lower than its peers in the same district.  Centaline Property saw sales involving  two units in the project over the past  weekend, with the largest transaction  valued at HK$120 million. \par\par Such keen transactions were rare for  more than a year, with various extra  stamp duties imposed to cool the sizzling housing market. \par\par Mainland purchasers blamed for  driving local home prices up to  unaffordable levels were put off by the  extra 15 percent Buyer's Stamp Duty  levied on non-permanent residents.  That was followed by measures to rein  in purchases by non-first-time buyers. \par\par Yielding to pressure from the real  estate sector, the government decided  in May to relax its curbs by making the  six-month grace period for resellers  more lenient. "This will provide a conceptual boost to potential buyers,'' Ng  said. \par\par Although mainlanders' buying  power is nowhere near its zenith, it has  picked up steam. About 10 percent of  recent purchasers at four high-end  projects - Arezzo, The Pavilia Hill, the  Harbourside in Tsim Sha Tsui by Hang  Lung Properties (0101), and 8 LaSalle  in Ho Man Tin by Kerry Properties  (0683) - were mainland residents, according to Midland. \par\par Meanwhile, in the secondary market, registrations for properties worth  more than HK$10 million reached 952  in the last three months, up 38.2 percent  from the 689 in the second quarter, data  compiled by Hong Kong Property  Services showed. \par\par "The resale market has improved,  but not as remarkably as the primary  market,'' said Midland's residential  chief Sammy Po Siu-ming. \par\par Some new homes were reportedly  even cheaper than secondary flats. But  that may be about to change. \par\par Pavilia Hill raised prices of its latest  apartments by 3 to 5 percent, while  Arezzo cut incentives by 0.25 percentage points for the batch launched earlier  this week.  \par\par The Harbourside, having sold 250  apartments in stocks, put four special  flats out to tender in a bid to test upper  price limits. "With lots of units being  sold, the developer will not mind selling  fewer at higher prices,'' Po said. "Prices  for luxury flats will edge up by 3 to 5  percent in the fourth quarter.'' \par\par Some are even banking on the soon- to-be-launched Shanghai-Hong Kong  Stock Connect to lift the upscale property market, citing fatter profits for  bankers and fund managers, as well as  an upbeat economic outlook. \par\par "The effect will be short-lived and  limited to the psychological level," said  Paul Tang Sai-on, chief economist at  Bank of East Asia (0023). \par\par "The benefits will mainly fall to the  financial sector. Only factors of the real  economy such as the unemployment  rate and interest rate will have a bearing  on the housing market.'' \par\par adam.xu@singtaonewscorp.com  \par
