Students should retreat and return roads to citizens 学生应撤离 还道路给市民 \par
\par
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ \par









\par\par 　　The occupation movement has gone through a turbulent start, an extremely disturbing dark night in Mong Kok and an exhausting torture. The participating university and secondary school students at this moment have come to a time for retreat, whether it is for their own safety, studies and families or avoiding arousing greater public grievance due to blockage of major roads in the urban centres.\par\par 　　The occupation in Mong Kok and Causeway Bay resulting from the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0  movement has caused blockage in many roads seriously affecting traffic in Kowloon and Hong Kong. It has a great impact on residents and small businesses in various districts as well as the SAR's economic activities. Resentment keeps growing in the people and sectors affected, creating a heated atmosphere. For Mong Kok with people of all kinds, it even involves triad interests. The confrontation between \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0  and anti-\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0  groups creates an environment for bad elements to cause trouble. Earlier, police used pepper spray there to suppress those who caused conflicts but the situation did not turn peaceful. It is still perilous.\par\par Road blockage causes great public resentment\par\par 　　The city's major roads belong to all Hong Kong citizens, not the protesters who are rallying there. The citizens have the right to use them. But the demonstrators raised a banner of protest and totally deprived of the citizens' rights, which runs counter to their principle of "democracy and human rights". It shows that they are doing things completely for themselves without caring about other's rights and interests. If this continues, it will certainly anger the public.\par\par 　　If the students do not want to be in confrontation with the citizens and the target of public criticism, completely failing with lack of public support, they should leave the areas they occupy as soon as possible and return the roads to the citizens.\par\par 　　Students who stay behind hope to guard their position, protecting the student representatives' bargaining chips with the government. Hence even when some organizers urged them to leave the high-risk Mong Kok area, some still insisted on staying.\par\par 　　The overall strategy of the occupation is to impact the economy as a means to force the central and SAR governments to give in. The more it affects the citizens' lives, the greater the public resentment, the higher the price society pays and the higher the pressure on the administration.\par\par Don't undermine bargaining chips with public opinion changing for the worse\par\par 　　But this risky strategy is a double-edged sword. The longer it is used, the greater the impact on the citizens, which even affects their livelihood. Public resentment will certainly become more heated with their most direct criticisms on those who occupy their places. It will result in weakening public support and even universal condemnation.\par\par 　　In recent days, there have been emotional citizens and businessmen condemning the protesters. This is only the tip of the iceberg of discontent over occupation participants. There are still many citizens affected who are complaining in their own social circles.\par\par 　　Students who stayed behind said that the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0  organizers do not represent them. But have they thought if they represent the citizens affected? Have the students properly respected the rights of those citizens who do not agree with them or agree with them but not their strategy?\par\par 　　The occupation movement has actually gone too far expanding from Admiralty to Causeway Bay and Mong Kok. Before there is a sharp turn in public opinion, at least leaving the major roads will reduce the destructive force. The students should also think for themselves and families quickly returning to their studies and family lives to prevent ruining their future while losing their valuable family relations.\par\par Published in the Sing Tao Daily\par\par on October 8\par\par Vocabulary\par\par turbulent (adj) ―― 动荡的\par\par disturbing (adj) ―― 使人震惊的\par\par impact (n) ―― 冲击resentment (n) ―― 愤恨 confrontation (n) ―― 对峙suppress (v) ―― 镇压rally (v) ―― 集会banner (n) ―― 旗帜\par\par deprive (v) ―― 剥夺\par\par expand (v) ―― 扩展\par\par Useful Terms\par\par urban centre ―― 市中心\par\par triad interest ―― 黑社会利益\par\par double-edged sword ―― 双刃剑\par\par universal condemnation ―― 千夫所指\par\par social circle ―― 社交圈\par\par Did you know?\par\par 　　Frustrated government and police officials have again appealed to demonstrators to clear main roads in Admiralty. They warned of more severe traffic jams. About 26,000 primary and special school students in the occupied districts of Central-Western and Wan Chai returned to school on Tuesday, on top of 30,000 secondary students in the districts. Classes in the areas' kindergartens will remain suspended. Emergency services have been hard hit by the traffic jams. Students and workers tried to get back to normal life after 10 days of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0  but that led to tailbacks totalling more than 20 kilometres at the morning peak stretching from Hong Kong Island to Kowloon. The longest tailback at one point was 5.7 kilometres from Queen's Road East to Aberdeen Wholesale Fish Market. Also jammed were Tai Hang and Island North, Waterloo Road and Gascoigne Road in Kowloon.\par\par Q&A\par\par 1.	The word _____ in the first paragraph is the opposite of "comfortable".\par\par 2.	It is time for the university and secondary school students participating in the occupation movement to _____.\par\par 3.	In the passage, the word _____ means "completely".\par\par 4.	The condemnations are only the tip of the iceberg of discontent over occupation participants because __________________________________________.\par\par 5.	According to the last paragraph, the students should at least leave the major roads to reduce the _____ force that may follow.\par\par Answers\par\par 1.	exhausting\par\par 2.	retreat\par\par 3.	totally\par\par 4.	there are still many citizens affected who are complaining in their own social circles\par\par 5.	destructive\par\par 翻译UGeorge\par\par 学生应撤离 还道路给市民\par\par 　　占领运动经历了风云激荡的开头、惊心动魄的旺角黑夜，以及疲惫不堪的煎熬，在这个时刻，参与的大中学生，无论为自己安全、学业和家人设想，或者避免因堵塞市中心主要道路引起更大民愤，都已到了应撤退的时候。\par\par 　　由\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 占领中环\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0 运动衍生出来的占领旺角及铜锣湾行动，令多条道路被堵，严重影响港九交通，对各区居民和做生意的小商户，以至全港经济活动，冲击极大。受影响人士和界别的怨气与日俱增，气氛火爆。旺角更因品流复杂，甚至牵涉黑社会利益，\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 占中\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0 和反\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 占中\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0 者的对峙，营造了不良分子乘机捣乱的氛围。早阵子警方使用胡椒喷雾在旺角镇住冲突者，但是乱局并没有就此化解，依然危机四伏。\par\par 堵塞公路引起极大民愤\par\par 　　市区的主要道路，是属于全港市民而不是属于集会的人士，市民都有道路的使用权，但示威者举起了抗争旗帜，就完全剥夺了市民的权利，与他们的「民主、人权」原则背道而驰，显出他们完全只为自己，不顾别人的人权与利益，如再继续下去，必会触发公众怒火。\par\par 　　学生如果不想自己处于与市民的对立面，成为众矢之的，因失去民心而全输，就应尽早撤离占领区，将道路还给市民。\par\par 　　留守现场的学生，是希望坚守阵地，保住学生代表与政府谈判的筹码。故此，即使有组织者呼吁他们撤离旺角这个高危区，始终有部分人士坚持留守。\par\par 　　今次整个占领行动的策略，是以打击经济作为逼使中央和港府让步的手段。民生影响愈大，民怨愈沸腾，社会代价愈高，对执政者的压力就愈大。\par\par 防民意逆转削谈判筹码\par\par 　　不过，这套兵行险着的策略，是一把双刃剑。当时间愈拖愈长，市民受打击愈来愈重，甚至影响生计b口，民怨的确会愈来愈沸腾，而最直接的不满对象是占领者，令其民意支持度日弱，甚至受到千夫所指。\par\par 　　这几天在旺角和铜锣湾，都经常有情绪激动的小市民和小商人痛斥示威者，这只是不满占领行动者的冰山一角，还有不少受影响市民在相熟圈子里吐苦水。\par\par 　　留守学生认为\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 占中\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0 组织者不代表自己，但是他们可曾想过，他们又何曾代表到那些受影响的市民？对于不认同学生理念，或者认同他们理念却不认同他们手法的市民，学生们有没有适当尊重其权利？\par\par 　　占领行动由金钟扩展到铜锣湾和旺角，本来就越过了火位。趁民意未大幅逆转前，至少撤离主要道路，以减少破坏力。学生也应为自己和家人设想，尽快回复正常学业和家庭生活，以免前途受损，还赔上可贵的亲情。\par\par 刊于十月八日《星岛日报》\par\par  \par
