\par\par Gaming hub sees 17pc rise in mainland tourists during National Day break as protests hit HK\par\par \par\par The number of mainland visitors to Macau over the week-long National Day holiday surged 17 per cent year on year as tourists avoided Hong Kong due to \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b\cf6 Occupy Central\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f15 \b0\cf0  protests that paralysed parts of the city.\par\par Mainland visitor arrivals to Hong Kong were up just 5.4 per cent over the “golden week” holiday period, significantly lower than the 16 per cent increase last year.\par\par However, those extra visitors to Macau were unlikely to lift revenue for the six casino operators this month.\par\par VIP high rollers, who account for 60 per cent of casino revenues, are still wary of the gaming enclave amid an anti-corruption drive on the mainland.\par\par Meanwhile, junket operators, which bring VIP spenders into casinos, continue to grapple with tightened liquidity. Kimren, the junket operator whose former principal ran off owing HK$8 billion in April, has been squabbling with sub-operator Xilong over finances, and that is expected to affect VIP numbers for Melco Crown Entertainment’s Altira and SJM Holdings’ Grand Lisboa casinos.\par\par Detailed gaming data for last month released yesterday showed that a weak VIP segment was mainly responsible for the 11.7 per cent year-on-year decline in gross gaming revenue. The decrease in VIP gaming volume widened to 25.7 per cent from 19 per cent in August, making September the worst-performing month since January 2011.\par\par Mass table revenue grew 15.2 per cent year on year last month, stabilising in the mid-teens after three consecutive months of decelerating growth. But a Nomura note published yesterday warned that “monthly mass table growth could drop to the low teens for the remainder of the year given tough comparisons”.\par\par China Union Gaming said in a note: “While the headline visitation numbers reported during golden week 